= Introduction and definition

== Definition of $lmip0 [k,n]$, first proposition.

The equality $mipstar = RE$ established by Ji, Natarajan, Vidick, Wright and Yuen @JNVWY reveals that entangled multi-prover interactive proofs are extraordinarily powerful: every recursively enumerable language admits such a proof. The standard model places no constraint on the entanglement shared by the provers — the shared quantum state may be arbitrary, in arbitrary dimension. This paper asks a natural structural question: _what happens when the shared entanglement is constrained to be local?_

We introduce a localized model $lmip0 [k,n]$ — for _Localized_ $mipstar$ — in which the provers share $n$ independent copies of a fixed quantum resource, but each interaction is restricted to a bounded-size *window* of that resource. Concretely, in each round the verifier selects a *fresh* copy and opens a window of at most $k$ qubits (distributed among the provers); the provers' answers for that round must be generated by measurements supported on the opened qubits only. If the verifier wants to test two different windows, it must do so in two rounds (and hence spend two independent copies). This enforces a clean separation between *local correlation size* (the parameter $k$) and *repetition budget* (the parameter $n$).

The full parameterization of the model is $lmip0 (r, p) [k, n]$, where $(r, p)$ are the standard interactive proof parameters — number of provers, rounds, completeness, and soundness — and $[k, n]$ are the _locality parameters_: $k$ bounds the number of qubits that can be jointly accessed in a single round (hence an effective per-round Hilbert space dimension at most $2^k$), and $n$ is the number of independent copies of the resource available to the protocol. The use of square brackets for the locality parameters distinguishes them syntactically from the standard parameters in parentheses. The base class is then defined by taking unions:
$ lmip0 [k,n] = union.big_(r,p) lmip0 (r, p)[k,n], $
$ lmip0 = union.big_(k,n) lmip0 [k,n]. $

In an analog way to the difference between $mipstar$ and $mipstarzero$, we have $lmip$ and $lmip0$. We choose to focus on $lmip0$ because we have a combinatorial approach, then we don't want randomness.
The interest of this model rests on a precise observation. The proof that $mipstar = RE$ requires the shared entangled state to have _arbitrarily large dimension_, growing with the instance. By bounding the amount of entanglement that can be operationally mobilized in a single interaction (at most $k$ qubits), and by enforcing that each round draws from a fresh independent copy, we impose an explicit locality-and-budget structure on the usable correlations. The resulting hierarchy in $[k, n]$ interpolates between constant-dimensional nonlocal games and the full power of $mipstar$, and raises concrete threshold questions: for which growth rates of $k$ and $n$ (as functions of the input size) does $lmip [k,n]$ recover $RE$?

We begin by recalling the formal definition of $mipstar$ and the key theorems that motivate our model.

= Formal definition of $mipstar$

#let HH = $cal(H)$

== General definition

We recall the standard definition of multi-prover interactive proof systems with entanglement. The parameters are the number of provers $r$, the number of rounds $p$, the completeness parameter $c$, and the soundness parameter $s$.

*Definition 1* ($mipstar_0 (r, p)$). A language $cal(L)$ belongs to $mipstar (r, p)$ if there exists a polynomial-time verifier $V$ interacting with $r$ non-communicating provers $P_1, dots, P_r$ over $p$ rounds of communication, such that:

+ *Shared entanglement.* Before the protocol begins, the provers share an arbitrary quantum state
  $ ket(psi) in HH_1 times.o HH_2 times.o dots.c times.o HH_r $
  where each $HH_i$ is a Hilbert space of _arbitrary finite dimension_. No restriction is placed on $ket(psi)$: it may be entangled in any way, in any dimension.

+ *Strategy.* Upon receiving question $q_i$ from the verifier, prover $P_i$ performs a measurement $\{M^((i))_(a|q_i)\}_a$ on their local subsystem $HH_i$ and returns the outcome $a$. The joint probability of outcomes $(a_1, dots, a_r)$ given questions $(q_1, dots, q_r)$ is
  $ p(a_1, dots, a_r | q_1, dots, q_r) = bra(psi) M^((1))_(a_1|q_1) times.o dots.c times.o M^((r))_(a_r|q_r) ket(psi). $

+ *Completeness.* If $x in cal(L)$, there exist a state $ket(psi)$ and measurements such that $Pr[V "accepts"] >= 1$ (we have $c=1$).

+ *Soundness.* If $x in.not cal(L)$, for _every_ state $ket(psi)$ (of every dimension) and _every_ choice of measurements, $Pr[V "accepts"] <= 1/2$ (we have $s = 1/2$).

The class $mipstarzero$ is defined as $union.big_(r,p) mipstarzero (r, p)$, allowing arbitrarily many provers and rounds with perfect completeness and bounded-error soundness.

In the $mipstar$ class, instead of fixing the completeness and soundness parameters to $1$ and $1/2$, we take unions over all $c, s$ such that $c - s >= 1/"poly"(|x|)$, allowing for arbitrary completeness-soundness gaps.

== Two-prover, one-round characterization

A fundamental simplification result shows that two provers and a single round suffice.

*Theorem 1* (see @JNVWY). $mipstarzero = mipstarzero (2, 1)$.

That is, every language recognizable by an entangled multi-prover interactive proof system is already recognizable by a _two-prover, one-round_ protocol with perfect completeness and soundness $1\/2$. In this simplified model, the protocol consists of a single exchange:

#block(inset: (left: 1.5em))[
  1. The verifier samples a pair of questions $(q_A, q_B)$ and sends $q_A$ to prover $A$, $q_B$ to prover $B$.

  2. The provers, who share $ket(psi) in HH_A times.o HH_B$, each measure their subsystem and return answers $a, b$.

  3. The verifier evaluates a predicate $V(q_A, q_B, a, b)$ and accepts or rejects.
]

This is precisely the framework of a _nonlocal game_, and the supremum of the acceptance probability over all quantum strategies is the _entangled value_ $omega^*$ of the game.

== The role of unbounded dimension in $mipstar = RE$

The following is the landmark result that motivates our investigation.

*Theorem 2* (Ji, Natarajan, Vidick, Wright, Yuen @JNVWY). $mipstar (2, 1, 1, s) = RE$ for some constant $s < 1$.

The proof constructs, for each Turing machine $M$, a nonlocal game $cal(G)_M$ such that:
- if $M$ halts, then $omega^*(cal(G)_M) = 1$ (a perfect strategy exists in finite dimension $d$, where $d$ depends on the halting time of $M$);
- if $M$ does not halt, then $omega^*(cal(G)_M) < 1$ (no strategy in any dimension achieves value $1$).

A crucial feature of this construction is that the entangled value is defined as
$ omega^*(cal(G)) = sup_(d >= 1) sup_(ket(psi) in CC^d times.o CC^d) sup_({M_(a|q)}, {N_(b|q')}) Pr["win"], $
and the supremum over $d$ is _essential_. For a halting machine with halting time $T$, the dimension $d$ of the optimal strategy may grow as a function of $T$, and no uniform bound on $d$ exists across all instances. In other words, the full power of $mipstar = RE$ relies on the provers' ability to use shared entanglement of _arbitrarily large dimension_.

*Remark.* If the dimension is bounded by a fixed constant $d$, the resulting class $mipstar (2,1,s,d)$ is known _not_ to capture all of $RE$; indeed, for fixed $d$, the entangled value $omega^*_d (cal(G))$ is computable by semidefinite programming, so the class collapses to a decidable complexity class.

= Definition of $lmip0 [k,n]$

#definition(name: [$lmip0 (r,p)[k,n]$])[

  A language $cal(L)$ belongs to $lmip0 (bold(r),bold(p))[bold(k),bold(n)]$ if there exists a polynomial-time verifier $V$ interacting with $bold(r)$ non-communicating provers $P_1, dots, P_bold(r)$ over $bold(p)$ rounds, such that:

  + *i.i.d. shared resource.* Before the protocol begins, the provers share $n$ independent copies of a fixed $r$-partite quantum state:
    $ ket(Psi) = ket(psi)^(times.o n). $
    Each copy are distributed among the $r$ provers with this following map $π : [n] -> [r]$, then the provers $p in [r]$ has the state $ket(psi)_()$

  + *One fresh copy per round.* The verifier uses at most one copy per round, and never reuses a copy. Formally, the verifier chooses an injective map $t mapsto j_t in [n]$. In particular, necessarily $p <= n$.

  + *Window locality (size $k$).* In each round $t in [p]$, the verifier selects a window $S_t subset [N]$ with $|S_t| <= k$ and sends questions $q_1^t, dots, q_r^t$ to the provers (including, if needed, a description of $S_t$). Each prover $P_i$ must generate their answer $a_i^t$ by a measurement that acts nontrivially only on the qubits of the chosen copy $j_t$ whose labels lie in $S_t$, together with any private workspace. Equivalently, for each prover $P_i$ and each round $t$, every POVM element can be written as
    $ M^((i,t))_(a_i|q_i^t) = tilde(M)^((i,t))_(a_i|q_i^t) times.o I, $
    where $tilde(M)^((i,t))_(a_i|q_i^t)$ acts on prover $P_i$'s qubits in copy $j_t$ with labels in $S_t$, and $I$ is the identity on all other qubits (including all other copies).

  + *Completeness and soundness.* If $x in cal(L)$, there exist a state $ket(psi)$ and a window-local strategy achieving $Pr[V "accepts"] = 1$. If $x in.not cal(L)$, then for every choice of $ket(psi)$ and every window-local strategy, $Pr[V "accepts"] <= 1/2$.

  We define $lmip0 [k,n] = union.big_(r,p) lmip0 (r,p)[k,n]$, and $lmip0 = union.big_(k,n) lmip0 [k,n]$.
]


