When we use the word *local*, we mean that two behaviours are *close* to each other, in the sense that one can be obtained from the other by a small modification. The main reason for introducing this notion is that, in practice, an observed event does not appear from nowhere. It is produced by an underlying process.

Indeed, an experiment is usually performed through a sequence of elementary steps. At each step, there may be noise, imperfections, small deviations, or even deliberate modifications. What we finally observe is only the outcome of the whole process, not the internal evolution itself. From this point of view, a piece of data should not be seen as an isolated object, but as the visible trace of a hidden sequential mechanism.

This is the reason why we introduce the notion of a *trace* $tau_i$. A trace represents the observable record of a process that is not directly accessible. Our goal is to understand the observed data by postulating constraints on the hidden process that produced it. In particular, we assume that this hidden process evolves in a locally coherent way, meaning that its successive configurations cannot change arbitrarily, but only through small perturbations. This motivates the notion of *local event*.

A local event is therefore not just an observed input-output pair. It represents an elementary observable step that is compatible with a hidden process evolving continuously in a discrete sense. In other words, the randomness that we observe at the level of traces is not taken as primitive. Instead, it is explained as the visible effect of an underlying process whose evolution is constrained by a notion of local continuity.

With this perspective, an experiment or a measurement can be described as a sequence of elementary local events. A single observed datum is then the result of a whole path through the space of locally coherent behaviours.

To connect this idea with interactive protocols, we distinguish between different levels of description. On the one hand, there is the physical implementation of the experiment, which we may think of as a collection of laboratories or devices performing concrete operations. On the other hand, there are agents who communicate with the verifier and may alter, transmit, or reinterpret the information. This distinction is important because the physical process itself may be constrained by locality and continuity, while the communicating agents may behave strategically or even maliciously.

In this interpretation, the laboratory represents the concrete physical process that produces outcomes according to the instructions it receives. The student, or more generally the external agent, acts as an interface between the verifier and the laboratory. This agent may carry the resource, choose how to implement the requested experiment, transmit the answers, and possibly modify the protocol or the reported outcome. The purpose of this distinction is to separate the hidden physical generation of the data from the adversarial layer that may affect what is actually communicated.

Our aim is therefore not only to study which correlations are possible, but also to model how an observed behaviour can be generated through a sequential process subject to local constraints, and how this process may be altered by intermediate agents. This gives a more dynamic point of view on non-local games and interactive protocols.

We can start by a simple model that is, we have a agent that go to different laboratory to do experimentation, he collect the data and return to the verifier. We lost the order of the data, then we can define :

